‘ THE gods have heard my prayers, Lyce. I have my revenge. You are turning into an old woman, yet would fain hide it, and drink and play and love as ever.

Love turns away from your wrinkles; nor will purple gauzes and jewellery bring back your youth. Where is the beauty that I remember, the charms which made you second only to Cinara ?—Cinara, who died in her prime, while you live on for

ever, for young men to moralize on and laugh at.'

The Ode is a sequel to 3. 10, in which he complained of Lyce’s high airs‚ and warned her not to try her 'lover's patience too long.
